        <h2 id="adoption" style="font-family:var(--serif);font-size:1.4rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--or);margin-bottom:1.5rem" class="reveal">🐾 Adoption & reservation</h2>
        <div class="faq-list reveal">
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">How do I reserve a puppy? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">Reservation starts with direct contact (contact form or phone), followed by a visit to the kennel. A deposit of CHF 500 is required to confirm your reservation; the balance is settled on the day the puppy leaves. We do not accept any firm reservation without a prior visit — we want to see you interact with our dogs.</div></div></div>
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">At what age do puppies leave? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">Our puppies leave the kennel at a minimum of 8 weeks, in accordance with Swiss animal welfare legislation. Some puppies stay until 10–12 weeks if we feel they benefit from additional socialisation time.</div></div></div>
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">Can we visit the kennel? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">Absolutely, and we strongly encourage it. Visits are by appointment only, Monday to Saturday. Please do not drop by unannounced — our dogs need undisturbed rest periods for their wellbeing.</div></div></div>
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">Is there a waiting list? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">Yes, for the most sought-after puppies (blue-eyed Pomsky, orange Pomeranians). Joining the waiting list is free — a deposit is only requested when we confirm a litter matching your criteria.</div></div></div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="prices" style="font-family:var(--serif);font-size:1.4rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--or);margin:3rem 0 1.5rem" class="reveal">💰 Prices & payment</h2>
        <div class="faq-list reveal">
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">What are your prices? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">Pomsky F1/F2: CHF 2,500–3,200 depending on coat and eye colour. Pomeranian: CHF 2,000–2,800. Siberian Husky: CHF 1,800–2,500. Prices include FCI pedigree, full health record, first vaccination, deworming, microchip, and a welcome kit (scent blanket, toy, transition kibbles).</div></div></div>
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">What payment methods do you accept? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">Bank transfer (Swiss IBAN), Twint, and cash. We do not accept card payments. The balance must be settled before or on the day of departure — no puppy leaves with an outstanding invoice.</div></div></div>
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">Is the deposit refundable? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">The deposit is refundable only if we are unable to fulfil the agreed litter. If you withdraw, the deposit remains with the kennel but may be transferred to a future litter within 12 months.</div></div></div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="health" style="font-family:var(--serif);font-size:1.4rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--or);margin:3rem 0 1.5rem" class="reveal">🩺 Health & vaccinations</h2>
        <div class="faq-list reveal">
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">What health guarantees do you offer? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">Every puppy leaves with a veterinary health certificate dated within 72 hours. We provide a 2-year genetic guarantee against serious hereditary conditions certified by our testing. Our breeding animals are all tested for hip dysplasia, cardiac, and ocular conditions.</div></div></div>
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">Is the puppy vaccinated? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">Yes. Each puppy receives its first vaccination before departure, plus full deworming. The official health record is handed over with the puppy. Your vet will schedule the booster at 12 weeks.</div></div></div>
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">Is the puppy microchipped? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">Yes, microchipping is mandatory in Switzerland and is done before departure. Initial registration in the AMICUS national database is included in the price. You will need to update your contact details in the system after adoption.</div></div></div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="breeds" style="font-family:var(--serif);font-size:1.4rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--or);margin:3rem 0 1.5rem" class="reveal">🐕 The breeds</h2>
        <div class="faq-list reveal">
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">Is the Pomsky suitable for apartment living? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">Yes, the Pomsky adapts very well to apartment life provided it gets sufficient exercise (two daily walks of at least 30 minutes each) and mental stimulation. It can be vocal when under-stimulated — worth considering if you have close neighbours.</div></div></div>
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">Pomsky F1, F2, F3 — what's the difference? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">F1 = 50% Pomeranian / 50% Husky (direct cross). F2 = two F1 Pomskies crossed. F3 = two F2 Pomskies. Generally, the higher the generation, the smaller and more consistent the size. Our F1s are the largest (8–14kg) with the greatest appearance variability — often the most beautiful surprises.</div></div></div>
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">Is a Husky the right fit for me? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">The Husky is an extraordinary dog — but a demanding one. It needs intense daily exercise, space, and company (it suffers alone). If you want a calm, low-maintenance dog, the Husky is probably not your match. If you love running, hiking, skiing — you will find the perfect partner.</div></div></div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="shipping" style="font-family:var(--serif);font-size:1.4rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--or);margin:3rem 0 1.5rem" class="reveal">🚗 Transport & delivery</h2>
        <div class="faq-list reveal">
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">Do you deliver puppies to other countries? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">We can arrange a halfway handover for families near the Swiss border (eastern France, Haute-Savoie, Rhône-Alpes). Home delivery is not offered. For longer distances, we can refer you to approved specialist pet transporters.</div></div></div>
          <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question">Can we collect our puppy on a weekend? <span class="icon">+</span></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer__inner">Yes, Saturday handovers are available. We prefer to avoid Friday evenings (risk of the puppy arriving when everyone is about to be out all day Monday).</div></div></div>
        </div>
